SIMPLE: fall
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fall
<hw>Fall</hw> <pr>(f⟦add⟧l)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Fell</conjf> <pr>(f⟦ecr⟧l)</pr>; <pos>p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Fallen</conjf> <pr>(f⟦add⟧l"'n)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Falling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>feallan</ets>;
akin to D. <ets>vallen</ets>, OS. & OHG. <ets>fallan</ets>, G.
<ets>fallen</ets>, Icel. <ets>Falla</ets>, Sw. <ets>falla</ets>, Dan.
<ets>falde</ets>, Lith. <ets>pulti</ets>, L. <ets>fallere</ets> to
deceive, Gr. <grk>sfa`llein</grk> to cause to fall, Skr.
<ets>sphal</ets>, <ets>sphul</ets>, to tremble. Cf. <er>Fail</er>,
<er>Fell</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, to cause to fall.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To Descend, either suddenly or gradually; particularly, to descend
by the force of gravity; to drop; to sink; <as>as, the apple
<ex>falls</ex>; the tide <ex>falls</ex>; the mercury <ex>falls</ex> in
the barometer.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I beheld Satan as lightning <qex>fall</qex> from heaven.</q>
<rj><qau>Luke x. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cease to be erect; to take suddenly a recumbent
posture; to become prostrate; to drop; <as>as, a child totters and
<ex>falls</ex>; a tree <ex>falls</ex>; a worshiper <ex>falls</ex> on his
knees.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>fell</qex> at his feet to worship him.</q> <rj><qau>Rev.
xix. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To find a final outlet; to discharge its waters; to
empty; -- with <xex>into</xex>; <as>as, the river Rhone <ex>falls</ex>
into the Mediterranean</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To become prostrate and dead; to die; especially, to
die by violence, as in battle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A thousand shall <qex>fall</qex> at thy side.</q> <rj><qau>Ps.
xci. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He rushed into the field, and, foremost fighting,
<qex>fell</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To cease to be active or strong; to die away; to
lose strength; to subside; to become less intense; <as>as, the wind
<ex>falls</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To issue forth into life; to be brought forth; --
said of the young of certain animals.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To decline in power, glory, wealth, or importance;
to become insignificant; to lose rank or position; to decline in weight,
value, price etc.; to become less; <as>as, the price <ex>falls</ex>;
stocks <ex>fell</ex> two points.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am a poor <qex>fallen</qex> man, unworthy now⟦br⟧
To be thy lord and master.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The greatness of these Irish lords suddenly <qex>fell</qex> and
vanished.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J. Davies.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To be overthrown or captured; to be
destroyed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Heaven and earth will witness,⟦br⟧
If Rome must <qex>fall</qex>, that we are innocent.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To descend in character or reputation; to become
degraded; to sink into vice, error, or sin; to depart from the faith; to
apostatize; to sin.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us labor therefore to enter into that rest, lest any man
<qex>fall</qex> after the same example of unbelief.</q> <rj><qau>Heb.
iv. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>To become insnared or embarrassed; to be entrapped;
to be worse off than before; <as>as, to <ex>fall</ex> into error; to
<ex>fall</ex> into difficulties</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>To assume a look of shame or disappointment; to
become or appear dejected; -- said of the countenance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cain was very wroth, and his countenance <qex>fell</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. iv. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have observed of late thy looks are <qex>fallen</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>To sink; to languish; to become feeble or faint;
<as>as, our spirits rise and <ex>fall</ex> with our
fortunes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>To pass somewhat suddenly, and passively, into a
new state of body or mind; to become; <as>as, to <ex>fall</ex> asleep;
to <ex>fall</ex> into a passion; to <ex>fall</ex> in love; to
<ex>fall</ex> into temptation.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <def>To happen; to to come to pass; to light; to befall;
to issue; to terminate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Romans <qex>fell</qex> on this model by chance.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sit still, my daughter, until thou know how the matter will
<qex>fall</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ruth. iii. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They do not make laws, they <qex>fall</qex> into customs.</q>
<rj><qau>H. Spencer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>15.</sn> <def>To come; to occur; to arrive.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The vernal equinox, which at the Nicene Council <qex>fell</qex> on
the 21st of March, <qex>falls</qex> now [1694] about ten days
sooner.</q> <rj><qau>Holder.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>16.</sn> <def>To begin with haste, ardor, or vehemence; to rush
or hurry; <as>as, they <ex>fell</ex> to blows</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They now no longer doubted, but <qex>fell</qex> to work heart and
soul.</q> <rj><qau>Jowett (Thucyd. ).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>17.</sn> <def>To pass or be transferred by chance, lot,
distribution, inheritance, or otherwise; <as>as, the estate
<ex>fell</ex> to his brother; the kingdom <ex>fell</ex> into the hands
of his rivals.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>18.</sn> <def>To belong or appertain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If to her share some female errors <qex>fall</qex>,⟦br⟧
Look on her face, and you'll forget them all.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>19.</sn> <def>To be dropped or uttered carelessly; <as>as, an
unguarded expression <ex>fell</ex> from his lips; not a murmur
<ex>fell</ex> from him.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>To fall abroad of</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to
strike against; -- applied to one vessel coming into collision with
another.</cd> -- <col><b>To fall among</b></col>, <cd>to come among
accidentally or unexpectedly.</cd> -- <col><b>To fall astern</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to move or be driven backward; to be left
behind; as, a ship <xex>falls astern</xex> by the force of a current, or
when outsailed by another.</cd> -- <col><b>To fall away</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To lose flesh; to become lean or emaciated; to
pine.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To renounce or desert allegiance; to revolt
or rebel.</cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To renounce or desert the faith; to
apostatize.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧These . . . for a while believe, and in time of
temptation <xex>fall away</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Luke viii. 13.</au>
<sd>(d)</sd> <cd>To perish; to vanish; to be lost.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧How . . .
can the soul . . . <xex>fall away</xex> into nothing?⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Addison.</au> <sd>(e)</sd> <cd>To decline gradually; to fade; to
languish, or become faint.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧One color <xex>falls away</xex>
by just degrees, and another rises insensibly.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Addison.</au>
-- <col><b>To fall back</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To recede or
retreat; to give way.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To fail of performing a
promise or purpose; not to fulfill.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To fall back
upon</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To fall back on</b></col></mcol>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <cd>To retreat for safety to (a stronger
position in the rear, as to a fort or a supporting body of troops).</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To have recourse to (a reserved fund, a more reliable
alternative, or some other available expedient or support).</cd> --
<col><b>To fall calm</b></col>, <cd>to cease to blow; to become
calm.</cd> -- <col><b>To fall down</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To
prostrate one's self in worship.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧All kings shall <xex>fall
down</xex> before him.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Ps. lxxii. 11.</au> <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>To sink; to come to the ground.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Down fell</xex> the
beauteous youth.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Dryden.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To bend or
bow, as a suppliant.</cd> <sd>(d)</sd> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>To sail or
drift toward the mouth of a river or other outlet.</cd> -- <col><b>To
fall flat</b></col>, <cd>to produce no response or result; to fail of
the intended effect; as, his speech <xex>fell flat</xex>.</cd> --
<col><b>To fall foul of</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>
<cd>To have a collision with; to become entangled with</cd> <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>To attack; to make an assault upon.</cd> -- <col><b>To fall
from</b></col>, <cd>to recede or depart from; not to adhere to; as,
<xex>to fall from</xex> an agreement or engagement; <xex>to fall
from</xex> allegiance or duty.</cd> -- <col><b>To fall from
grace</b></col> <fld>(M. E. Ch.)</fld>, <cd>to sin; to withdraw from the
faith.</cd> -- <col><b>To fall home</b></col> <fld>(Ship Carp.)</fld>,
<cd>to curve inward; -- said of the timbers or upper parts of a ship's
side which are much within a perpendicular.</cd> -- <col><b>To fall
in</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To sink inwards; as, the roof <xex>fell
in</xex>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <cd>To take one's proper
or assigned place in line; as, <xex>to fall in</xex> on the right.</cd>
<sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To come to an end; to terminate; to lapse; <as>as, on
the death of Mr. B., the annuuity, which he had so long received,
<ex>fell in</ex></as>.</cd> <sd>(d)</sd> <cd>To become operative.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧The reversion, to which he had been nominated twenty years
before, <xex>fell in</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Macaulay.</au> -- <col><b>To fall
into one's hands</b></col>, <cd>to pass, often suddenly or unexpectedly,
into one's ownership or control; as, to spike cannon when they are
likely <xex>to fall into the hands</xex> of the enemy.</cd> --
<col><b>To fall in with</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To meet with
accidentally; as, <xex>to fall in with</xex> a friend.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>To meet, as a ship; also, to discover or come
near, as land.</cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To concur with; to agree with; as,
the measure <xex>falls in with</xex> popular opinion.</cd> <sd>(d)</sd>
<cd>To comply; to yield to.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧You will find it difficult to
persuade learned men <xex>to fall in with</xex> your projects.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Addison.</au> -- <col><b>To fall off</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To
drop; as, fruits <xex>fall off</xex> when ripe.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To
withdraw; to separate; to become detached; as, friends <xex>fall
off</xex> in adversity.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Love cools, friendship <xex>falls
off</xex>, brothers divide.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To
perish; to die away; as, words <xex>fall off</xex> by disuse.</cd>
<sd>(d)</sd> <cd>To apostatize; to forsake; to withdraw from the faith,
or from allegiance or duty.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those captive tribes . . . <qex>fell off</qex>⟦br⟧
From God to worship calves.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(e)</sd> <cd>To forsake; to abandon; as, his customers <xex>fell
off</xex>.</cd> <sd>(f)</sd> <cd>To depreciate; to change for the worse;
to deteriorate; to become less valuable, abundant, or interesting;
<as>as, a <xex>falling off</xex> in the wheat crop; the magazine or the
review <xex>falls off</xex></as>.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧O Hamlet, what a
<xex>falling off</xex> was there!⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> <sd>(g)</sd>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>To deviate or trend to the leeward of the point
to which the head of the ship was before directed; to fall to
leeward.</cd> -- <col><b>To fall on</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To meet
with; to light upon; as, we have <xex>fallen on</xex> evil days.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To begin suddenly and eagerly.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Fall
on</xex>, and try the appetite to eat.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Dryden.</au>
<sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To begin an attack; to assault; to assail.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Fall on</xex>, <xex>fall on</xex>, and hear him not.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Dryden.</au> <sd>(d)</sd> <cd>To drop on; to descend on.</cd> --
<col><b>To fall out</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To quarrel; to begin to
contend.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A soul exasperated in ills <qex>falls out</qex>⟦br⟧
With everything, its friend, itself.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To happen; to befall; to chance.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧There
<xex>fell out</xex> a bloody quarrel betwixt the frogs and the
mice.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>L'Estrange.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <cd>To
leave the ranks, as a soldier.</cd> -- <col><b>To fall over</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To revolt; to desert from one side to another.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To fall beyond.</cd> <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>To fall
short</b></col>, <cd>to be deficient; as, the corn <xex>falls
short</xex>; they all <xex>fall short</xex> in duty.</cd> -- <col><b>To
fall through</b></col>, <cd>to come to nothing; to fail; as, the
engageent <xex>has fallen through</xex>.</cd> -- <col><b>To fall
to</b></col>, <cd>to begin.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Fall to</xex>, with eager
joy, on homely food.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Dryden.</au> -- <col><b>To fall
under</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To come under, or within the limits
of; to be subjected to; as, they <xex>fell under</xex> the jurisdiction
of the emperor.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To come under; to become the
subject of; <as>as, this point did not <ex>fall under</ex> the
cognizance or deliberations of the court; these things do not <ex>fall
under</ex> human sight or observation.</as></cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To
come within; to be ranged or reckoned with; to be subordinate to in the
way of classification; <as>as, these substances <ex>fall under</ex> a
different class or order.</as></cd> -- <col><b>To fall upon</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To attack.</cd> [See <cref>To fall on</cref>.]
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To attempt; to have recourse to.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧I do not
intend <xex>to fall upon</xex> nice disquisitions.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Holder.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To rush against.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Fall</xex> primarily denotes descending motion,
either in a perpendicular or inclined direction, and, in most of its
applications, implies, <xex>literally</xex> or <xex>figuratively</xex>,
velocity, haste, suddenness, or violence. Its use is so various, and so
mush diversified by modifying words, that it is not easy to enumerate
its senses in all its applications.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fall</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fall
<hw>Fall</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To let
fall; to drop.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For every tear he <qex>falls</qex>, a Trojan bleeds.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To sink; to depress; <as>as, to <ex>fall</ex> the
voice</as>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To diminish; to lessen or lower.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Upon lessening interest to four per cent, you <qex>fall</qex> the
price of your native commodities.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To bring forth; <as>as, to <ex>fall</ex>
lambs</as>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To fell; to cut down; <as>as, to <ex>fall</ex> a
tree</as>.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. & Local, U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fall</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fall
<hw>Fall</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of falling; a
dropping or descending be the force of gravity; descent; <as>as, a
<ex>fall</ex> from a horse, or from the yard of ship</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of dropping or tumbling from an erect
posture; <as>as, he was walking on ice, and had a
<ex>fall</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Death; destruction; overthrow; ruin.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They thy <qex>fall</qex> conspire.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pride goeth before destruction, and a haughty spirit before a
<qex>fall</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. xvi. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Downfall; degradation; loss of greatness or office;
termination of greatness, power, or dominion; ruin; overthrow; <as>as,
the <ex>fall</ex> of the Roman empire</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Beholds thee glorious only in thy <qex>fall</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The surrender of a besieged fortress or town ;
<as>as, the <ex>fall</ex> of Sebastopol</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Diminution or decrease in price or value;
depreciation; <as>as, the <ex>fall</ex> of prices; the <ex>fall</ex> of
rents.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A sinking of tone; cadence; <as>as, the
<ex>fall</ex> of the voice at the close of a sentence</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Declivity; the descent of land or a hill; a
slope.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Descent of water; a cascade; a cataract; a rush of
water down a precipice or steep; -- usually in the plural, sometimes in
the singular; <as>as, the <ex>falls</ex> of Niagara</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>The discharge of a river or current of water into
the ocean, or into a lake or pond; <as>as, the <ex>fall</ex> of the Po
into the Gulf of Venice</as>.</def> <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>Extent of descent; the distance which anything
falls; <as>as, the water of a stream has a <ex>fall</ex> of five
feet</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>The season when leaves fall from trees;
autumn.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What crowds of patients the town doctor kills,⟦br⟧
Or how, last <qex>fall</qex>, he raised the weekly bills.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>That which falls; a falling; <as>as, a
<ex>fall</ex> of rain; a heavy <ex>fall</ex> of snow.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <def>The act of felling or cutting down.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>fall</xex> of timber.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>15.</sn> <def>Lapse or declension from innocence or goodness.
Specifically: The first apostasy; the act of our first parents in eating
the forbidden fruit; also, the apostasy of the rebellious
angels.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>16.</sn> <def>Formerly, a kind of ruff or band for the neck; a
falling band; a faule.</def> <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>17.</sn> <def>That part (as one of the ropes) of a tackle to
which the power is applied in hoisting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fall herring</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a herring
of the Atlantic (<spn>Clupea mediocris</spn>); -- also called
<altname>tailor herring</altname>, and <altname>hickory
shad</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>To try a fall</b></col>, <cd>to try a
bout at wrestling.</cd> <au>Shak.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fallacious</ent>⟦br⟧
